<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-869-840  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 869 840.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  Nov 1989 v10 n11 p20(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Piecing together a distributed system at Albany Medical Center.andO;(integrated clinical information system; includes related articleon user perspective)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Albany Medical Center (AMC) solved the problem of creating acost-effective integrated clinical information system by usingleading-edge technology.andP;  The solution was to use a relationaldatabase to act as a traffic cop and translator so that previouslyincompatible information systems could communicate.andP;  AMC decidedon Libra Health Technology's multivendor integration product,Lifenet, which uses a Unify relational database and acts as atranslator.andP;  The system revolves around the HP 9000 Model 825,which uses translation tables for transactions between differentsystems.andP;  AMC also employs Second Foundation Inc's ProTouch systemsince it allows physicians and nurses to choose from structuredmenus to create clinical records.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Libra Health Technology (products)Second Foundation Inc. (products).andO;Topic:     Hospital Information SystemsMedical RecordsRelational Data BasesLocal Area NetworksAutomationIntegrated Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Albany Medical Center's integrated clinical information center.andO;(chart)About the system. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>